These are the streets where the top 100 water guzzlers live in the drought-ravaged City of Cape Town, which effectively has 121 days of usable water left.While the average household uses roughly 20,000l of water a month &mdash; less than 1,000l a day &mdash; the city&rsquo;s top consumer in Haywood Road&sbquo; Crawford&sbquo; used a staggering 702,000l in a month.Dam levels in the city had dropped to 33% on Monday&sbquo; 1.5% down from the previous week. With the last 10% of a dam&rsquo;s water mostly not useable&sbquo; dam levels are effectively at 23%.Collective daily water consumption in the city stands at 837-million litres a day&sbquo; far exceeding a target of 700-million litres a day. At this drawn-down rate&sbquo; there are effectively 121 days of useable water left."We may not have control over the weather&sbquo; but we do have control over our use of potable water for nonessential purposes. Our actions can change the scenario&sbquo;" said mayor Patricia de Lille.The city plans to publish the identities of residents or commercial properties once they have paid a fine or appeared in court for flouting water restrictions.The top 100 users with the highest water usage per month are located in:1. Haywood Road&sbquo; Crawford &mdash; 702,000l.2. Manenberg Avenue&sbquo; Manenberg &mdash; 655,000l.3. Boundary Road&sbquo; Lansdowne &mdash; 557,000l.4. Upper Hillwood Road&sbquo; Bishop&rsquo;s Court &mdash; 554,000l.5. Norwich Drive&sbquo; Bishop&rsquo;s Court &mdash; 500,000l.6. Pear Lane&sbquo; Constantia &mdash; 461,000l.7. Barchan Circle&sbquo; Big Bay &mdash; 457,000l.8. Hoeveld Road&sbquo; La Concorde &mdash; 443,000l.9. Montana Road&sbquo; Colorado Park &mdash; 441,000l.10. Charnwood Avenue&sbquo; Tokai &mdash; 431,000l.11. Pallotti Road&sbquo; Durheim &mdash; 424,000l.12. Heron Street&sbquo; Danarand &mdash; 417,000l.13. Vesperdene Road&sbquo; Green Point &mdash; 409,000l.14. Main Road&sbquo; Green Point &mdash; 398,000l.15. De Wet Road&sbquo; Fresnaye &mdas